Males are diagnosable by the combination of malar space shorter than (~0.5
x
) clypeal lateral, S1 process apical surface with a distinct longitudinal ridge, and in lateral view having a distinctly acute anterior apical angle, sloping strongly toward sternum posteriorly. Females are diagnosable by the combination of malar space less than half as long as clypeal lateral, clypeus sparsely punctate medially (i≥2d), and absence of longitudinal depressions on the paraocular area.
